In article <PC123.92Nov25122044@grus.cus.cam.ac.uk>, pc123@cus.cam.ac.uk 
(Pete Chown) writes:
> 
> First, let me emphasise the main disadvantages of using Diffie-Hellman
> key exchange.  Firstly you can be spoofed - if the person you are
> talking to is not who you think he is, you can be tricked into giving
> away information.  Thus Diffie-Hellman does not provide for
> authentication, and so can only be used against passive eavesdroppers.

There are ways to do an authenticated Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
See e.g.:

C. G. Guenther,
An Identity-Based Key-Exchange Protocol,
in: Adv. in Cryptology - EUROCRYPT '89,
Springer, Berlin 1990, pp. 29--37.

F. Bauspiess, H.-J. Knobloch,
How to Keep Authenticity Alive in a Computer Network,
in: Adv. in Cryptology - EUROCRYPT '89,
Springer, Berlin 1990, pp. 38--46.

P. Horster, H.-J. Knobloch,
Cryptographic Protocols and Network Security,
in: G. G. Gable, W. J. Caelli  (Eds.):
IT Security: The Need for International Cooperation, Proceedings of the
IFIP TC11 Eighth International Conference on Information Security,
North-Holland, Amsterdam 1992, pp. 249-263.


